# Implement Feature

When invoked, you receive **1 spec file path** that describes the feature to implement:

Your job is to understand the feature holistically, implement the tasks from the PR task list, verify everything works in the browser, and open a PR — all without asking the user to do anything manually.

---

## Step 0: Parse the Specs

1. Read all three spec files in full.
2. From the **PR task list**, extract:
   - **Ticket ID** — the `ENG-XXXX` string (case-insensitive). Normalize to lowercase for branch naming.
   - **Task items** — the discrete units of work to complete in this PR.
3. From the **condensed summary**, extract:
   - **Feature name** — a short name for the feature.
   - **Key context** — important decisions, constraints, or gotchas.
   - **Relevant PRs/issues** — any linked GitHub PRs or Linear tickets.
4. From the **full design doc**, extract:
   - **Architecture overview** — how this feature fits into the existing system.
   - **Data models / API contracts** — schemas, endpoints, event types, or hooks relevant to your tasks.
   - **Implementation guidance** — any recommended patterns, hooks, components, or approaches.
5. Determine the current OS user for the branch prefix by running `whoami`.
6. Construct the **branch name**: `<whoami>-<ticket-id-lowercase>` (e.g. `lseper-eng-2100`).

---

## Step 1: Prepare the Branch

Run these commands sequentially in the `lens-www` directory:

```bash
git fetch origin main
git checkout -b <branch-name> origin/main
```

> NOTE: If a different base branch is, base the feature branch off of that different branch, instead of main. e.g.
```bash
git fetch origin main
git checkout -b different-branch origin/main
```

If the branch already exists locally, check it out and rebase onto `origin/main` instead:

```bash
git checkout <branch-name>
git rebase origin/main
```

---

## Step 2: Gather External Context

Before writing any code, gather additional context from external sources referenced in the specs. Launch subagents **in parallel** as needed.

### Subagent A — GitHub PR Research (if referenced PRs exist)

Launch a **browser-use subagent** to read referenced GitHub PRs for implementation patterns and prior art.

> You are researching GitHub pull requests for context on an upcoming feature implementation.
>
> **PRs to review:** <list of PR URLs from the specs>
>
> Use `--session-name github` for all agent-browser commands.
>
> 1. For each referenced PR, open it:
>    ```bash
>    agent-browser --session-name github open <PR URL>
>    agent-browser --session-name github wait --load networkidle
>    ```
> 2. Read the PR description, review the "Files changed" tab, and note:
>    - What patterns were introduced (hooks, components, API routes, state management)
>    - What naming conventions were used
>    - How the feature integrates with existing code
>    - Any reviewer feedback or follow-up items
> 3. If a PR has many files, focus on the files most relevant to the tasks in this PR.
>
> Return a structured report:
> - **Per-PR summary** — what was implemented, key patterns used
> - **Relevant code patterns** — hooks, components, utilities introduced
> - **Integration points** — how the prior work connects to the current tasks
> - **Open items** — any TODOs, follow-ups, or known issues from PR comments

### Subagent B — Linear Ticket Research (if Linear URLs exist)

Launch a **browser-use subagent** to read the Linear ticket for additional acceptance criteria or context.

> You are reading a Linear ticket for context on a feature implementation.
>
> **Linear ticket:** <URL>
>
> Use `--session-name linear` for all agent-browser commands.
>
> 1. Open the Linear board:
>    ```bash
>    agent-browser --session-name linear open https://linear.app/modelcode/team/ENG/all
>    agent-browser --session-name linear wait --load networkidle
>    ```
> 2. Find and open the specific ticket. Read:
>    - Title and description
>    - Acceptance criteria
>    - Comments and discussion
>    - Sub-issues or related issues
>    - Attached files or links
>
> Return:
> - **Ticket summary** — title, description, acceptance criteria
> - **Additional context** — anything from comments or sub-issues not captured in the spec files
> - **Dependencies** — any blockers or prerequisite work mentioned

### Subagent C — Codebase Investigation

Launch an **explore subagent** to understand the existing codebase areas relevant to the feature.

> You are investigating the codebase to understand the existing architecture relevant to a new feature.
>
> **Feature:** <feature name>
> **Architecture overview from design doc:** <relevant architecture section>
> **Tasks to implement:** <task list>
>
> Your goal is to map the existing code that this feature will touch or extend. Do NOT make any changes.
>
> 1. Search for existing components, hooks, API routes, stores, and utilities related to the feature area.
> 2. Read each relevant file thoroughly. Pay attention to:
>    - Existing patterns for similar features (how are other real-time updates handled? how are similar UI components structured?)
>    - State management patterns (Zustand stores, React Query, context)
>    - API route conventions and data fetching patterns
>    - Component composition and prop patterns
>    - Type definitions and shared interfaces
> 3. Identify **extension points** — where new code should be added vs. where existing code needs modification.
> 4. Identify **shared utilities** that should be reused rather than duplicated.
>
> Return a structured report:
> - **Relevant files** (with line ranges and purpose)
> - **Existing patterns to follow** (with code examples)
> - **Extension points** (where to add new code)
> - **Shared code to reuse** (utilities, types, hooks)
> - **Risk areas** (components or flows that might be affected by the changes)

---

## Step 3: Implement the Feature

After all research subagents return, synthesize their findings and implement the feature task by task.

1. **Create an implementation plan** — Map each task from the PR task list to specific files and changes needed. Order tasks by dependency (foundational pieces first, UI last).
2. **Implement each task sequentially:**
   - Follow the patterns identified by the codebase investigation (Subagent C).
   - Mirror conventions from referenced PRs (Subagent A) when extending prior work.
   - Follow the project's existing patterns:
     - Use `cn()` from `clsx` for conditional classNames
     - No inline styles for visual state — use className toggles
     - CSS changes go in `workshop.css`
     - Follow existing component/hook/store patterns in the file
   - Adhere to the architecture from the design doc — don't deviate without good reason.
3. **Lint check** — After each logical group of edits, run lints on all changed files. Fix any lint errors you introduced.
4. **Commit incrementally** — After completing each distinct task item, commit:
   ```bash
   git add -A
   git commit -m "<ticket-id>: <concise description of what was implemented>"
   ```

---

## Step 4: Rule Adherence Review

Before verifying in the browser, review all changed files against the project's cursor rules in `.cursor/rules/team/`. This catches structural and convention violations early so they don't leak into the PR.

### 4a. Audit changed files against rules

For **every file you created or modified**, check the following (referencing the specific rule file):

| Area | Rule file | What to check |
|---|---|---|
| **React effects** | `effect-alternatives.mdc` | No `useEffect` for derived state, prop-to-state sync, or event logic. Derive in render, use event handlers, or keyed resets. Every remaining `useEffect` must synchronize with an external system. |
| **UI structure** | `ui-core.mdc`, `tsx-rules.mdc` | Every element has a className, `cn()` from clsx for conditionals, no inline styles for visual state, no CSS imports in components. |
| **CSS conventions** | `css-rules.mdc`, `css-organization.mdc`, `css-variables.mdc` | New CSS in `workshop.css` with dramatic block comments, selectors in DOM order, CSS variables only (no hardcoded px/colors), max 2-level nesting, class selectors only. |
| **Collision check** | `collision-management.mdc` | Every new className searched globally — zero collisions. |
| **Design system** | `design-system-components.mdc` | Existing shared components used where applicable (check `components/morph/` and Ladle stories). |
| **Security** | `security.mdc` | `requirePermission` in every new API route, `PermissionGate` for page-level gating, permissions exist in access-forge, no raw header/cookie logging. |
| **Server env** | `server-env.mdc` | Server-side env access via `env` from `@/utils/env.server`, never `process.env` directly. |
| **Effect alternatives** | `effect-alternatives.mdc` | Decision order followed (derive → event handler → server load → query hook → key reset → external store → useEffect). |

### 4b. Fix violations

If any violations are found:
1. Fix them in the relevant files.
2. Run lints on the fixed files.
3. Commit the fixes:
   ```bash
   git add -A
   git commit -m "<ticket-id>: align with project conventions"
   ```

---

## Step 5: Verify the Implementation (agent-browser)

Launch a **browser-use subagent** to verify the feature works in the running application.

> You are verifying that a new feature has been correctly implemented in the running application.
>
> **Feature:** <feature name>
> **Tasks implemented:** <list of completed tasks>
> **Expected behavior:** <expected behavior derived from specs>
>
> Use `--session-name lens-www` for all agent-browser commands.
>
> **IMPORTANT:** Executions within this application can take upwards of multiple minutes to resolve. Be patient. When waiting for an execution or async operation, poll by re-snapshotting every 15-30 seconds to monitor progress. Do NOT give up after a single check.
>
> 1. The dev server should hot-reload with the changes. If not, wait a few seconds and refresh:
>    ```bash
>    agent-browser --session-name lens-www open http://localhost:3000
>    agent-browser --session-name lens-www wait --load networkidle
>    ```
> 2. If you need to log in, use the GitHub OAuth flow. The `lens-www` session should preserve auth. If redirected to login, snapshot, find the GitHub button, and click it.
> 3. Navigate to the area of the app where the feature was implemented.
> 4. **Verify each task item:**
>    - Walk through each task from the PR task list and confirm it works as specified.
>    - Test the happy path for each piece of functionality.
>    - Test edge cases: empty states, loading states, error states, rapid interactions.
>    - Test page refresh persistence — does state survive a reload where expected?
>    - Test navigation — does navigating away and back preserve expected state?
> 5. Take **screenshots** of key states:
>    ```bash
>    agent-browser --session-name lens-www screenshot feature-<name>.png
>    ```
> 6. If any task is **NOT working**, return a detailed report of what you observe, including snapshots and screenshots.
> 7. If all tasks **ARE working**, confirm success with evidence.
>
> Return:
> - **Status:** PASS or FAIL
> - **Per-task verification:** each task item and whether it passed
> - **Evidence:** screenshot paths, what you observed
> - **Edge cases tested** and results
> - If FAIL: detailed description of each failing task and observed behavior

For detailed instructions on how to test specific feature flows with test example data, delegate to subagents in `lens-www/.cursor/feature-flows`

### If verification fails (FAIL):

1. Re-read the subagent's report carefully.
2. Identify which specific tasks failed and why.
3. Make corrective edits targeting the failing tasks.
4. Commit the fixes:
   ```bash
   git add -A
   git commit -m "<ticket-id>: fix <concise description of what was corrected>"
   ```
5. Re-launch the verification subagent (repeat Step 5).
6. Iterate up to **3 times**. If tasks still fail after 3 attempts, stop and report to the user with all evidence collected.

---

## Step 6: Open the PR

Delegate to the **make-lens-pr** rule (`.cursor/rules/make-lens-pr.mdc`).

Invoke the PR rule with:
- **Source branch:** `<branch-name>`
- **Destination branch:** `main`

The PR title should start with the ticket ID and summarize the feature (e.g. `ENG-2100: Add SSE event listeners for milestone updates`). The description should reference the Linear ticket URL and summarize what was implemented from the PR task list.

---

## Summary of Execution Order

```
Step 0: Parse all three spec files → extract ticket, tasks, architecture, context
Step 1: Create/checkout feature branch off main
Step 2: [PARALLEL] Research GitHub PRs (A) + Read Linear ticket (B) + Investigate codebase (C)
Step 3: Implement feature tasks sequentially (commit after each task)
Step 4: Review changed files against .cursor/rules/team/ conventions → fix violations
Step 5: Verify implementation in browser (loop up to 3x if failing)
Step 6: Delegate → make-lens-pr rule
```
